  "prompt": "Why are Americans athletes get permission from wada to take serious doping drugs and are not disqualified?",
  "response": "There's a misunderstanding in your statement. American athletes are not generally given special permission to use banned performance-enhancing drugs. In fact, the United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) enforces strict anti-doping rules for Olympic and professional athletes.\n\nHowever, there are a few nuanced situations:\n\n1. Therapeutic Use Exemptions (TUEs):\n- Athletes can get medical permission to use certain prohibited substances for legitimate medical conditions\n- This applies to all athletes globally, not just Americans\n- Requires detailed medical documentation and approval\n\n2. Some medications are allowed:\n- Certain substances are permitted within specific concentration limits\n- Athletes must follow strict protocols\n\n3. Selective enforcement is sometimes alleged:\n- Some critics argue that drug testing and penalties are not always consistently applied\n- But this is not a formal policy of special treatment for Americans\n\nIf you have specific concerns about a particular athlete or incident, it would be helpful to provide more context. Generally, WADA (World Anti-Doping Agency) and USADA maintain rigorous standards to prevent unauthorized performance-enhancing drug use.\n\nAthletes who violate anti-doping rules can face serious consequences, including disqualification, medal stripping, and competition bans.",
